headline: Trump Sues JPMorgan and CEO Jamie Dimon Over ‘Debanking’ Claims
summary: President Donald Trump filed a lawsuit against  JPMorgan Chase  and its chief executive officer, Jamie Dimon, alleging that the bank’s decision to shutter the president’s accounts there in 2021 was politically motivated.  The lawsuit filed Thursday escalates Republican lawmakers’ pressure on the banking industry over claims that lenders are shuttering conservatives’ bank accounts on political grounds—allegations that  JPMorgan  and competitors including  Bank of America  have denied.  Alejandro Brito, Trump’s lawyer, filed the suit in state court in Florida’s Miami-Dade County.

headline: Trump sues JPMorgan Chase for $5bn in debanking row
summary: Donald Trump has filed a $5bn (£3.7bn) lawsuit against JPMorgan Chase (JPMC),  accusing it of debanking him and his business empire after his first term in the White House ended.  The US president claims America's largest bank by assets and its chief executive Jamie Dimon closed a number of personal and business accounts in February 2021, with 60 days' notice, for political reasons.  Mr Trump argues that he and his business interests were cut off from millions of dollars and suffered disruption as they scrambled to open bank accounts elsewhere.

headline: Trump sues JPMorgan for $5 billion, alleges the bank closed his accounts for political reasons
summary: President Donald Trump sued banking giant JPMorgan Chase and its CEO Jamie Dimon for $5 billion on Thursday over allegations that JPMorgan stopped providing banking services to him and his businesses for political reasons after he left office in January 2021.  The lawsuit, filed in Miami-Dade County court in Florida, alleges that JPMorgan abruptly closed multiple accounts in February 2021 with just 60 days notice and no explanation.  “JPMC debanked (Trump and his businesses) because it believed that the political tide at the moment favored doing so,” the lawsuit alleges.

headline: Trump's call for a 10% credit card rate cap is 'inconceivable'
summary: Trump called on Congress to implement a 10% cap on credit card interest rates, but Wolfe Research head of US policy and politics Tobin Marcus says that the odds of the cap coming to fruition are "essentially zero," highlighting unintended consequences for consumers. Marcus tells Market Catalysts Host Julie Hyman that some of the other affordability-focused efforts that Trump has called for — like banning large institutional investors from buying single-family homes — and the Credit Card Competition Act are unlikely, but not "inconceivable" like the credit card rate cap.
